feat(src): Use more granular status messages.

* Remove leading `PASSWORD_`, it's implied.
* `NOT_STRONG_ENOUGH` => `ALL_LETTERS_OR_NUMBERS`
* `SUCCESS` => `LONG_ENOUGH` if the password >= 12 characters.
* `SUCCESS` => `BLOOMFILTER_MISS` if the bloomfilter is used.

Merge pull request #34 from mozilla/owasp-data-set

feat(data): Use the datasets from the OWASP SecList. 
r=@TDA

feat(data): Use the datasets from the OWASP SecList.

Original source: https://github.com/danielmiessler/SecLists

This replaces the previous data set with data from OWASP top passwords list.
I have included the data for the top 100, 500, 1k, 10k, 100k, and 1M
passwords so we can experiment. I have created filtered lists of the top
10k, 100k and 1M, and generated a new build based on the filtered 100k list.

The advantage to this dataset is the popularity ranking. This allows us to
filters the known most popular 100k passwords instead of an unsorted
list of human readable passwords.

feat(src): Wrap bloomfilter.js with RequireJS constructs.

feat(src): Wrap bloomfilter.js with RequireJS constructs.

fixes #20

cleanup(scripts): Lots of script cleanup.

* Input/output filenames are passed into the scripts.
* Add the analyze-words.js script.
* Add bloomfilter to the package.json devDependencies list.
* Update password_filter.py to have easier to understand filtering rules to
  filter the passwords pre-checked in passwordcheck.js
* The number of bits to allocate for the bloomfilter is based on the
  dictionary length.
* Ensure the file generated by plaintext2bloom wraps the bloomfilter data with
  RequireJS constructs so no global variables are used.
* Change the output format files produced by plaintext2bloom.js
  * Output both `numberOfHashes` and `bloomFilterData`.
